// Ch6 Agile Test Planning and Risk Management â€” IDs 1491â€“1640 (150 questions)
{id:1491,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"How does test planning differ in Agile compared to traditional approaches?",options:["A. Agile test planning is lightweight iterative and updated each sprint","B. Agile has no test planning at all","C. Agile test planning is done once upfront and never revisited","D. Agile test planning is only done by the Scrum Master"],answer:0,explanation:"Agile test planning is lightweight and iterative â€” the team revisits and adapts the plan every sprint rather than writing a heavy upfront plan."},
{id:1492,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a product risk in Agile testing?",options:["A. A risk that the project will run over budget","B. A risk that the Scrum Master will leave the team","C. A risk that a feature of the product may fail to meet user needs or cause harm","D. A risk that the sprint will be cancelled"],answer:2,explanation:"Product risks relate to potential failures in the product itself â€” a feature may not work correctly or may not meet user expectations."},
{id:1493,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"easy",question:"What two factors are typically used to assess a risk?",options:["A. Sprint length and team size","B. Number of test cases and code coverage","C. Story points and velocity","D. Likelihood of occurrence and impact if it occurs"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk is typically assessed by multiplying or combining the likelihood of the risk occurring with the impact it would have if it did."},
{id:1494,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does risk mitigation mean in Agile testing?",options:["A. Ignoring low-priority risks","B. Taking actions to reduce the probability or impact of a risk","C. Transferring all risk to the Product Owner","D. Documenting all risks in a formal risk register"],answer:1,explanation:"Risk mitigation involves taking proactive actions â€” testing earlier, adding coverage, improving design â€” to reduce the probability or impact of a risk materialising."},
{id:1495,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is risk-based testing?",options:["A. An approach that prioritises test design and execution based on risk level","B. Testing only features that have previously had defects","C. Testing performed after a risk review meeting","D. Automated testing driven by a risk scoring tool"],answer:0,explanation:"Risk-based testing focuses testing effort where risk â€” likelihood Ã— impact â€” is highest, ensuring the most important areas are covered first."},
{id:1496,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is test estimation in Agile?",options:["A. Counting the exact number of test cases needed before the sprint","B. Setting the number of story points the tester will complete","C. Estimating the number of defects that will be found","D. Forecasting the effort time and resources needed for testing activities"],answer:3,explanation:"Test estimation forecasts the effort and time needed for testing, used during sprint planning to ensure realistic commitments."},
{id:1497,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the tester's primary contribution during sprint planning?",options:["A. Assigning tasks to developers","B. Writing the sprint goal","C. Providing testing effort estimates and flagging testability risks for planned stories","D. Ordering the product backlog"],answer:2,explanation:"Testers contribute testing estimates and identify testability concerns during sprint planning so the team can commit realistically."},
{id:1498,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the purpose of release planning in Agile?",options:["A. To assign developers to release tasks","B. To plan which features will be delivered by a given date across multiple sprints","C. To write the final test report","D. To freeze the product backlog permanently"],answer:1,explanation:"Release planning maps out which stories will be delivered across sprints to achieve a release goal by a target date."},
{id:1499,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a test strategy in Agile?",options:["A. A high-level description of how the team will approach testing â€” techniques tools and levels","B. A detailed plan of every test case to be executed","C. The Definition of Done for testing","D. A contract with the customer specifying test coverage"],answer:0,explanation:"A test strategy describes the overall testing approach â€” what techniques will be used, at what levels, and with which tools."},
{id:1500,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is an example of a product risk?",options:["A. A key developer leaving the team","B. The sprint being extended by two days","C. A payment feature failing under high load","D. The Product Owner being unavailable"],answer:2,explanation:"A payment feature failing under load is a product risk â€” it concerns the product's quality and reliability in operation."},
{id:1501,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is an example of a project risk?",options:["A. A login feature producing incorrect session tokens","B. A user interface being difficult to navigate","C. An API returning incorrect data","D. A critical team member becoming unavailable mid-sprint"],answer:3,explanation:"Project risks threaten the success of the project itself â€” losing a key resource is a project risk, not a product risk."},
{id:1502,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Agile what is iteration planning also known as?",options:["A. Release planning","B. Sprint planning","C. Backlog refinement","D. Risk review"],answer:1,explanation:"Iteration planning and sprint planning refer to the same event â€” planning the work for the next time-boxed iteration."},
{id:1503,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"Who is responsible for test planning in a mature Agile team?",options:["A. The whole team collaboratively","B. The lead tester alone","C. The Scrum Master","D. The Product Owner"],answer:0,explanation:"In mature Agile teams, test planning is a whole-team activity â€” everyone shares responsibility for quality and planning."},
{id:1504,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following techniques is MOST useful for identifying product risks in Agile?",options:["A. Velocity calculation","B. Counting the number of open defects","C. Running regression tests","D. Risk brainstorming with the whole team during sprint planning or refinement"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk brainstorming with the whole team â€” including developers testers and PO â€” is the most effective way to surface product risks early."},
{id:1505,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"medium",question:"A feature has a 90% chance of failure but the impact is negligible. How should this be treated?",options:["A. It should be treated as high priority because the probability is very high","B. Risk is low overall â€” the low impact offsets the high probability","C. It must be fixed in the next sprint","D. It should be escalated to the Product Owner immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Risk = likelihood Ã— impact. High probability with negligible impact results in a low overall risk level."},
{id:1506,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team identifies a risk that a third-party API may be unreliable. What is the BEST mitigation?",options:["A. Ignore it until the API fails in production","B. Remove the feature that depends on the API","C. Build and test a fallback mechanism and include API integration testing early in the sprint","D. Ask the Product Owner to accept the risk"],answer:2,explanation:"Proactive mitigation means building resilience and testing the dependency early â€” before it causes a production failure."},
{id:1507,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"In risk-based testing how does risk level affect test design?",options:["A. High-risk areas receive more thorough and diverse testing techniques","B. High-risk areas receive less testing to save time","C. Risk level has no effect on test design in Agile","D. Only the Scrum Master decides which areas get tested"],answer:0,explanation:"Risk-based testing allocates more coverage â€” more test cases and diverse techniques â€” to high-risk areas."},
{id:1508,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which estimation technique involves comparing a new story to a similar previously completed story?",options:["A. Planning Poker","B. Bottom-up estimation","C. Analogous estimation","D. Three-point estimation"],answer:2,explanation:"Analogous estimation uses historical data from similar past work to estimate effort for a new item."},
{id:1509,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why should testing tasks be explicitly included in sprint planning?",options:["A. To increase story point totals","B. Because the Scrum Guide requires it","C. To give testers more authority over the sprint","D. To ensure testing capacity is accounted for and testing is not an afterthought"],answer:3,explanation:"Explicitly planning testing tasks ensures the team accounts for test effort and avoids testing being squeezed out at sprint end."},
{id:1510,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does risk influence release planning in Agile?",options:["A. Risk has no place in release planning","B. High-risk features should be planned for early sprints to allow more time for defect resolution","C. Only low-risk features should be released first","D. Risk is only considered after the release"],answer:1,explanation:"Placing high-risk features in early sprints allows more time to discover and fix defects before the release date."},
{id:1511,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following BEST describes a lightweight Agile test strategy?",options:["A. A brief description of testing levels techniques and tools agreed by the whole team","B. A 50-page formal test plan document","C. A list of all test cases for the release","D. An automated test execution report"],answer:0,explanation:"Agile test strategies are brief and collaborative â€” just enough to align the team on approach without unnecessary documentation overhead."},
{id:1512,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"Who is MOST responsible for identifying product risks on an Agile team?",options:["A. The lead tester only","B. The Product Owner only","C. An external risk manager","D. The whole team â€” developers testers and Product Owner collaboratively"],answer:3,explanation:"Product risk identification is a whole-team activity â€” testers bring testing perspective, developers know technical risks, and the PO knows business impact."},
{id:1513,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team has only one person who understands a critical integration. What is the project risk?",options:["A. The integration will fail in production","B. The integration is too complex to test","C. Knowledge is siloed â€” if that person is unavailable the team cannot test or fix the integration","D. The Product Owner will reject the feature"],answer:2,explanation:"A single point of knowledge is a project risk â€” if that person is unavailable the whole team's progress is blocked."},
{id:1514,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the benefit of involving developers in test planning?",options:["A. It reduces the number of testers needed","B. Developers can identify technical risks and testability issues that testers alone may miss","C. It speeds up test execution","D. Developers can write test reports instead of testers"],answer:1,explanation:"Developer involvement in test planning surfaces technical risks early and improves testability of the solution from the start."},
{id:1515,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the MOST important outcome of iteration planning from a testing perspective?",options:["A. Agreed testing tasks estimates and acceptance criteria for all stories in the iteration","B. A complete list of test scripts","C. A formal test plan document","D. A risk register approved by the PMO"],answer:0,explanation:"The key testing outcome of iteration planning is agreed acceptance criteria and testing tasks with realistic estimates."},
{id:1516,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a risk register in Agile?",options:["A. A list of all bugs found in the sprint","B. A formal audit document produced at project close","C. A living document or backlog item list tracking identified risks their likelihood impact and mitigation actions","D. A report submitted to the PMO monthly"],answer:2,explanation:"A risk register tracks identified risks with their probability impact and mitigation actions â€” in Agile it is kept lightweight and regularly reviewed."},
{id:1517,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a risk matrix used for?",options:["A. Plotting test coverage against code complexity","B. Tracking defect counts per sprint","C. Estimating velocity for the next release","D. Visualising and prioritising risks by mapping likelihood against impact"],answer:3,explanation:"A risk matrix maps likelihood on one axis and impact on the other enabling teams to visually prioritise which risks need the most attention."},
{id:1518,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is risk acceptance in Agile?",options:["A. Fixing all risks before proceeding","B. A conscious decision by the team and Product Owner to proceed knowing a risk exists and its potential impact","C. Transferring the risk to the customer","D. Ignoring the risk without assessment"],answer:1,explanation:"Risk acceptance is a deliberate informed decision â€” the team acknowledges the risk and its potential consequences and chooses to proceed anyway."},
{id:1519,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is Planning Poker used for in Agile?",options:["A. Collaborative relative estimation of user story effort using cards","B. Risk assessment","C. Test case prioritisation","D. Defect severity rating"],answer:0,explanation:"Planning Poker is a consensus-based estimation technique where team members simultaneously reveal their effort estimates using numbered cards."},
{id:1520,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"A sprint has 5 stories but the team has not estimated testing effort for any of them. What is the MOST likely outcome?",options:["A. Testing will be completed on time automatically","B. The Scrum Master will add testing tasks automatically","C. Velocity will increase because there is less work","D. Testing will be rushed or skipped at sprint end causing quality issues"],answer:3,explanation:"Without explicit testing estimates testing tends to be squeezed at sprint end or skipped entirely causing quality debt."},
{id:1521,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a release burndown chart used for?",options:["A. Tracking defect counts across sprints","B. Showing remaining story points across all sprints toward a release goal","C. Tracking individual developer productivity","D. Monitoring CI pipeline build times"],answer:1,explanation:"A release burndown shows remaining work across all planned sprints giving the team visibility on whether the release goal is on track."},
{id:1522,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why should a test strategy in Agile include automation plans?",options:["A. Because all testing must be automated in Agile","B. To satisfy the Definition of Done","C. Automation decisions made late are expensive â€” planning automation approach early enables the right tests to be automated from the start","D. To reduce the number of testers on the team"],answer:2,explanation:"Early automation planning ensures the team invests in automation where it adds the most value and builds it incrementally rather than scrambling at release time."},
{id:1523,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does the Product Owner contribute to product risk identification?",options:["A. The PO provides business context â€” helping the team understand which features have the highest business impact if they fail","B. The PO has no role in risk identification","C. The PO writes the risk register","D. The PO decides which risks to ignore"],answer:0,explanation:"The PO's business knowledge is critical for assessing risk impact â€” they know which features matter most to users and the business."},
{id:1524,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which testing technique is MOST aligned with risk-based testing?",options:["A. Equivalence partitioning applied uniformly to all features","B. Running all tests in alphabetical order","C. Exploratory testing focused on high-risk areas combined with targeted automation","D. Testing only features with the most story points"],answer:2,explanation:"Risk-based testing directs exploratory and targeted testing effort toward high-risk areas where defects would have the greatest impact."},
{id:1525,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team consistently discovers that stories cannot be tested because dependencies are not ready. What should be addressed in iteration planning?",options:["A. The testers should work faster","B. The sprint should be extended","C. Testing should be deferred to the next sprint","D. Dependencies should be identified and resolved or the story should not enter the sprint"],answer:3,explanation:"Unresolved dependencies are a testability risk â€” iteration planning should surface them so stories are only accepted into the sprint when they are genuinely ready."},
{id:1526,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the three amigos meeting and how does it support test planning?",options:["A. A daily standup with only testers developers and the PO","B. A pre-sprint meeting where the PO developer and tester collaborate to clarify acceptance criteria and plan testing for a story","C. A retrospective with three team members","D. A meeting between three external stakeholders"],answer:1,explanation:"Three amigos meetings align the PO developer and tester on expected behaviour before development starts enabling accurate test planning."},
{id:1527,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team is building a banking app. Which technique would MOST effectively identify security risks early?",options:["A. Threat modelling workshops with developers security specialists and testers","B. Running unit tests","C. Checking velocity trends","D. Running regression tests"],answer:0,explanation:"Threat modelling is a structured risk identification technique that surfaces security risks early in the development process."},
{id:1528,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"hard",question:"A feature has a 20% chance of failure but would expose sensitive user data if it did. How should this be classified?",options:["A. Low risk â€” the probability is only 20%","B. Medium risk â€” log it and revisit next sprint","C. No risk â€” 20% chance means 80% chance of success","D. High risk â€” the impact of a data exposure is severe enough to classify it as high even with moderate probability"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk is probability Ã— impact. Severe impact â€” like data exposure â€” elevates overall risk even when probability is moderate."},
{id:1529,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team discovers a high-risk area late in the release. Regression tests do not cover it. What is the BEST immediate action?",options:["A. Release anyway and fix in production","B. Ask the Product Owner to accept the risk without additional testing","C. Add targeted tests for the high-risk area before release and delay if necessary","D. Remove the feature from the release"],answer:2,explanation:"Discovering uncovered high-risk areas late requires targeted test addition even at the cost of a short delay â€” releasing untested high-risk code is riskier."},
{id:1530,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has limited time before release and 200 regression tests. How should risk-based testing guide their decision?",options:["A. Run all 200 tests regardless of time constraints","B. Prioritise and run tests covering highest-risk areas first so the most important coverage is achieved within the available time","C. Skip regression entirely and focus only on new features","D. Run tests in the order they were written"],answer:1,explanation:"Risk-based prioritisation ensures the most important tests are run first â€” if time runs out the remaining tests cover lower-risk areas."},
{id:1531,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team routinely underestimates testing effort causing stories to roll over. What is the ROOT cause to investigate?",options:["A. Testing complexity is not being accounted for during planning â€” stories are estimated for development only","B. The testers are too slow","C. The sprint is too short","D. The Product Owner adds too many stories"],answer:0,explanation:"Systematic underestimation usually means testing is not explicitly estimated â€” only development effort is counted during planning."},
{id:1532,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"During sprint planning a tester raises that a story is not testable because acceptance criteria are vague. What should happen?",options:["A. Accept the story and test it based on assumptions","B. The tester should write acceptance criteria alone","C. The story should not enter the sprint until acceptance criteria are clarified â€” it fails the Definition of Ready","D. Move it to the next sprint without discussion"],answer:2,explanation:"A story without clear acceptance criteria cannot be reliably tested â€” it should not enter the sprint until clarified per the Definition of Ready."},
{id:1533,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's velocity is 40 points per sprint and they have 400 points of work remaining. Release is in 8 sprints. What should they do?",options:["A. Commit to delivering all 400 points in 8 sprints","B. Increase velocity by skipping testing","C. Add more developers to the team immediately","D. Flag the risk immediately â€” at current velocity they will deliver exactly 320 points â€” the PO must prioritise the most valuable work"],answer:3,explanation:"At 40 pts/sprint over 8 sprints = 320 pts delivered vs 400 needed. This is a release risk requiring immediate PO prioritisation decisions."},
{id:1534,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's test strategy relies entirely on automated unit tests. What is the MOST significant gap?",options:["A. Unit tests are not valid in Agile","B. Integration system and user acceptance testing are absent â€” defects at those levels will be undetected","C. The team has too many tests","D. Unit tests cannot be automated"],answer:1,explanation:"Unit tests alone leave integration system and UAT levels uncovered â€” a whole-pyramid strategy is needed to catch all defect types."},
{id:1535,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A product risk is identified as unlikely but catastrophic. What is the MOST appropriate testing response?",options:["A. Apply thorough testing to the risk area to either confirm or reduce the risk level","B. Ignore it because probability is low","C. Accept the risk without testing","D. Only test it if it appears in the sprint backlog"],answer:0,explanation:"Even low-probability catastrophic risks warrant thorough testing â€” the potential impact justifies the investment to confirm or reduce the risk."},
{id:1536,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team identifies that their testing environment is unstable â€” tests fail intermittently without code changes. What kind of risk is this?",options:["A. Product risk","B. Business risk","C. Security risk","D. Project risk â€” environment instability threatens the team's ability to deliver and get reliable test results"],answer:3,explanation:"An unstable test environment is a project risk â€” it undermines the reliability of test results and threatens delivery timelines."},
{id:1537,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"How does pair testing support whole-team test planning?",options:["A. It reduces the team to two members","B. It shares testing knowledge across the team â€” developers gain testing skills and testers gain technical insight","C. It eliminates the need for automated testing","D. It satisfies regulatory testing requirements"],answer:1,explanation:"Pair testing spreads quality knowledge across the team building a culture where quality is everyone's responsibility."},
{id:1538,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the relationship between the Definition of Ready and test planning for an iteration?",options:["A. They are unrelated concepts","B. The Definition of Ready replaces test planning","C. The Definition of Ready ensures stories entering the iteration have clear enough acceptance criteria for testers to plan testing","D. Only the Scrum Master defines the Definition of Ready"],answer:2,explanation:"The Definition of Ready acts as a quality gate â€” stories meeting it have sufficient clarity for testers to plan their testing approach before coding begins."},
{id:1539,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a FMEA and how can it be applied in Agile testing?",options:["A. Failure Mode and Effects Analysis â€” a structured technique for identifying what can fail how likely it is and what the impact would be applied to high-risk product areas","B. A framework for managing engineering activities â€” used to plan sprints","C. A formal audit methodology for regulated industries only","D. A way to estimate story points for defect fixes"],answer:0,explanation:"FMEA systematically identifies failure modes and their effects â€” applying it to high-risk product areas in Agile surfaces risk early and informs test design."},
{id:1540,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team reassesses risks at the start of every sprint. Why is this important?",options:["A. It is a regulatory requirement","B. It is required by the Scrum framework","C. New code changes introduced each sprint create new risks â€” the risk landscape changes continuously in Agile","D. It ensures the risk register is always 100% complete"],answer:2,explanation:"Agile's incremental delivery means new risks emerge every sprint â€” continuous re-assessment keeps risk management current and relevant."},
{id:1541,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the difference between risk mitigation and risk avoidance?",options:["A. They are the same strategy","B. Avoidance is cheaper than mitigation","C. Mitigation is only used for project risks","D. Mitigation reduces the probability or impact of a risk; avoidance eliminates the risk by removing the cause entirely"],answer:3,explanation:"Mitigation reduces but does not eliminate risk; avoidance removes the risk entirely by changing the design or approach to eliminate the risk source."},
{id:1542,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the T-shirt sizing estimation technique?",options:["A. Estimating test effort in hours for each story","B. Assigning relative size labels (XS S M L XL) to stories to give quick rough estimates without precise numbers","C. Measuring test coverage as a percentage of code","D. A method for sizing the test team"],answer:1,explanation:"T-shirt sizing assigns broad relative categories to stories enabling fast high-level estimation useful for release planning and roadmaps."},
{id:1543,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team always completes all sprint stories but no exploratory testing is ever done. What should change in sprint planning?",options:["A. Exploratory testing sessions should be explicitly planned as sprint backlog tasks with time allocated","B. Nothing â€” completing all stories is the goal","C. Exploratory testing should be done after the release only","D. Only the tester should decide when to do exploratory testing"],answer:0,explanation:"Exploratory testing finds defects that scripted tests miss â€” it must be explicitly planned and timeboxed in the sprint backlog to ensure it happens."},
{id:1544,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"How should non-functional requirements affect release planning?",options:["A. They are outside the scope of release planning","B. They can be tested after the release","C. The Product Owner has no interest in non-functional requirements","D. Non-functional requirements need testing time just like functional ones â€” performance security and accessibility tests should be planned across sprints"],answer:3,explanation:"Non-functional testing is often overlooked in sprint planning â€” explicitly planning performance security and usability testing across the release prevents last-minute gaps."},
{id:1545,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"What does shift-left mean in the context of an Agile test strategy?",options:["A. Moving the test team to the left side of the office","B. Running tests from left to right in alphabetical order","C. Introducing testing activities as early as possible â€” during requirements review and design rather than after coding","D. Reducing the number of test stages in the pipeline"],answer:2,explanation:"Shift-left means moving testing earlier in the lifecycle â€” catching defects in requirements and design is far cheaper than finding them after coding."},
{id:1546,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A product risk is identified as medium probability and high impact. How should the team respond?",options:["A. Accept it without action because probability is only medium","B. Actively mitigate through targeted testing design improvements and monitoring","C. Defer action to the next release","D. Assign sole responsibility to the tester"],answer:1,explanation:"Medium probability with high impact classifies as a high-priority risk requiring active mitigation not passive acceptance."},
{id:1547,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following is a sign that project risks are being poorly managed?",options:["A. Risks consistently materialise as crises rather than being anticipated and mitigated","B. The team discusses risks in every retrospective","C. The team maintains a lightweight risk list","D. The Product Owner reprioritises the backlog in response to risks"],answer:0,explanation:"Risks that repeatedly become crises indicate the team is reacting rather than proactively identifying and mitigating them."},
{id:1548,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"How does a working agreement support whole-team test planning?",options:["A. It replaces sprint planning","B. It is only relevant for the testing team","C. It codifies shared quality expectations â€” such as code review standards test coverage targets and DoD criteria â€” that all team members commit to","D. It is a legal document signed by stakeholders"],answer:2,explanation:"A working agreement establishes shared quality norms so the whole team aligns on standards before conflicts arise."},
{id:1549,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"After using risk-based testing a team releases software with several low-risk defects. What does this indicate?",options:["A. The risk assessment was wrong","B. The team should test everything equally next time","C. Risk-based testing is not valid in Agile","D. The approach is working as intended â€” low-risk defects are an acceptable residual risk that risk-based testing consciously accepts"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk-based testing deliberately focuses on high-risk areas â€” some low-risk defects escaping is an accepted trade-off for efficient test coverage allocation."},
{id:1550,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A new story added to the sprint mid-iteration changes the risk profile significantly. What should the team do?",options:["A. Ignore the risk change â€” the sprint plan cannot be altered","B. Re-assess risks for the sprint in response to the scope change and adjust testing priorities accordingly","C. Wait until the retrospective to discuss the new risk","D. Ask the tester to work overtime to cover the new risk"],answer:1,explanation:"Mid-sprint scope changes require a rapid risk re-assessment so testing priorities can be updated before coverage gaps appear."},
{id:1551,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team is releasing a medical device control application. Which risk identification approach is MOST appropriate?",options:["A. Structured hazard analysis such as FMEA combined with regulatory checklist review and whole-team risk workshops","B. Informal team discussion over coffee","C. Running unit tests and checking coverage","D. Reviewing the product backlog for incomplete stories"],answer:0,explanation:"Safety-critical systems require formal structured risk identification â€” FMEA and regulatory checklist reviews identify hazards that informal approaches miss."},
{id:1552,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team rates all risks as medium to avoid difficult conversations. What is the PRIMARY consequence?",options:["A. The team will deliver faster","B. The risk register becomes easier to manage","C. Stakeholders will be more satisfied","D. Critical high-impact risks are not properly prioritised â€” they receive the same attention as minor risks leading to missed critical defects"],answer:3,explanation:"Politically inflated risk ratings destroy the value of risk management â€” high-impact risks must be rated honestly to receive appropriate attention."},
{id:1553,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team has identified 30 product risks but only has capacity to actively mitigate 10. How should they proceed?",options:["A. Mitigate risks in the order they were identified","B. Prioritise by risk exposure (likelihood Ã— impact) and actively mitigate the top 10 â€” accept or monitor the rest with explicit awareness","C. Ask management to assign more testers","D. Defer all risk mitigation to after the release"],answer:1,explanation:"When capacity is limited prioritise by risk exposure â€” actively mitigate the highest risks and consciously accept lower ones with documented awareness."},
{id:1554,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team uses risk-based testing but their risk assessment is done only once at release start. What is the MAIN weakness?",options:["A. The assessment takes too long","B. Risk-based testing requires daily assessment","C. Risk profiles change as features are built and defects are found â€” a static risk assessment becomes outdated and misleading","D. The team will test too many features"],answer:2,explanation:"Risk is dynamic in Agile â€” new code new integrations and defect findings change the risk picture every sprint requiring continuous reassessment."},
{id:1555,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's estimates are consistently 50% lower than actual effort. Which root cause is MOST likely?",options:["A. Estimates do not account for testing complexity edge cases and defect investigation time â€” only happy-path development is being estimated","B. The team is not working hard enough","C. The sprint length is wrong","D. Story points are being inflated by the Product Owner"],answer:0,explanation:"Systematic underestimation usually means only the development happy path is estimated â€” testing complexity rework and investigation effort are invisible."},
{id:1556,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team has 10 stories in sprint planning and the tester raises that testing them all would take 12 days but the sprint is 10. The BEST resolution is:",options:["A. The tester should work faster","B. Carry over all testing to the next sprint","C. Remove the lowest-priority stories from the sprint so the remaining stories can be tested thoroughly within the sprint","D. Skip testing on stories the tester cannot reach"],answer:2,explanation:"Capacity-constrained sprints require scope reduction â€” not quality compromise. Lower-priority stories should be deferred to protect testing quality on the stories committed to."},
{id:1557,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"Halfway through a release a major architectural change is introduced that affects 60% of the product. What must happen to the release plan?",options:["A. Continue with the original plan â€” the architecture is a developer concern","B. Only update the sprint backlog for the current sprint","C. Ask management to extend the release date by 2 weeks","D. Re-plan the release â€” reassess risk re-estimate testing effort and update the roadmap to reflect the changed scope and risk profile"],answer:3,explanation:"A major architectural change invalidates large portions of the existing test strategy and risk assessment â€” a full release re-plan is required."},
{id:1558,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team discovers their test strategy focuses only on functional testing. A performance issue causes a production outage. What should change?",options:["A. Nothing â€” performance issues are the infrastructure team's responsibility","B. The test strategy must be expanded to include non-functional testing â€” performance load security and usability â€” as first-class concerns","C. Add more functional tests","D. Hire a separate performance testing team"],answer:1,explanation:"A production outage driven by performance exposes a strategy gap â€” non-functional testing must be part of the core Agile test strategy not an afterthought."},
{id:1559,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A product risk that was marked as low at the start of the release has grown to high due to new integrations. What does this demonstrate?",options:["A. Risk profiles are dynamic â€” risk levels must be continuously reassessed as the product evolves","B. The original risk assessment was wrong","C. Low risks should always stay low","D. New integrations do not affect existing risk ratings"],answer:0,explanation:"Risk is not static â€” new integrations dependencies or design decisions can elevate a previously low risk to high requiring updated mitigation."},
{id:1560,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team has no automated regression suite and is releasing every two weeks. What is the MOST significant project risk?",options:["A. The CI pipeline will be too slow","B. The Product Owner will reject stories","C. The development team will run out of work","D. Manual regression effort grows with each sprint â€” the team will eventually be unable to regression-test the full product within a sprint"],answer:3,explanation:"Without automation manual regression grows unsustainably â€” by mid-release the team cannot verify the full product in a sprint creating a compounding project risk."},
{id:1561,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A tester discovers that developers consistently write code that is hard to test. What is the MOST systemic solution?",options:["A. The tester should work harder to test untestable code","B. Hire more testers","C. Introduce testability as a design criterion â€” include it in the Definition of Done and discuss it in three amigos sessions before coding starts","D. Switch to a different programming language"],answer:2,explanation:"Testability problems are design problems â€” addressing them at source through DoD criteria and pre-development collaboration prevents the issue rather than managing it."},
{id:1562,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team finds that risk assessment in iteration planning adds 30 minutes to planning meetings. A manager asks them to remove it. The BEST response is:",options:["A. Agree â€” 30 minutes is too long","B. Retain it â€” 30 minutes of risk identification prevents hours or days of defect investigation and rework later","C. Move risk assessment to after the sprint","D. Delegate risk assessment to the tester only"],answer:1,explanation:"The ROI of 30 minutes of risk identification vastly outweighs the cost of undetected risks â€” removing it is false economy."},
{id:1563,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a checklist-based risk identification approach?",options:["A. Using a structured list of common risk areas derived from past projects to prompt the team to consider potential risks","B. Running automated tests against a predefined checklist","C. A regulatory compliance audit tool","D. A daily standup format for testers"],answer:0,explanation:"Checklist-based risk identification uses experience from previous projects to prompt teams to consider known risk areas they might otherwise overlook."},
{id:1564,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following BEST defines risk exposure?",options:["A. The number of risks identified","B. The total cost of testing activities","C. A combined measure of a risk's probability and impact often expressed as a score or rating","D. The number of defects in the backlog"],answer:2,explanation:"Risk exposure combines probability and impact into a single measure used to prioritise which risks need the most urgent attention."},
{id:1565,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the main difference between a test plan and a test strategy?",options:["A. They are the same document","B. A test plan is written by the tester; a test strategy by the Scrum Master","C. A test strategy is automated; a test plan is manual","D. A test strategy describes the overall approach and principles; a test plan applies that strategy to a specific release or sprint"],answer:3,explanation:"A test strategy is high-level and durable; a test plan is specific to a scope â€” it applies the strategy to a particular release sprint or feature."},
{id:1566,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is contingency planning in risk management?",options:["A. Adding extra story points to the sprint to cover risks","B. Planning what to do if a risk occurs â€” a reactive response plan activated when mitigation fails","C. Removing risky stories from the backlog","D. Hiring contractors to cover project risks"],answer:1,explanation:"Contingency planning defines what actions to take if a risk materialises despite mitigation efforts â€” it is a fallback plan."},
{id:1567,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does risk-based testing change as a release approaches?",options:["A. Near release the focus shifts to verifying that high-risk mitigations are effective and residual risks are at an acceptable level","B. Risk-based testing becomes less important near release","C. All testing stops near release to prepare documentation","D. The team switches to only automated testing"],answer:0,explanation:"As release approaches risk-based testing shifts to verification â€” confirming mitigations worked and residual risk is acceptable for release."},
{id:1568,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why is testing effort often underestimated in Agile teams?",options:["A. Testers work too slowly","B. Story points are always inaccurate","C. The Product Owner does not understand testing","D. Testing is seen as a single activity rather than a set of activities including design execution defect investigation and regression"],answer:3,explanation:"Testing encompasses multiple activities â€” design execution defect investigation and regression â€” each with its own effort that is often overlooked in estimation."},
{id:1569,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a sprint goal and how does it affect test planning?",options:["A. A list of all stories in the sprint","B. A short objective that guides the sprint â€” test planning should ensure coverage of the features that support achieving the sprint goal","C. The Definition of Done for the sprint","D. The maximum velocity the team will commit to"],answer:1,explanation:"The sprint goal provides focus â€” testers should prioritise coverage of the features that most directly enable achievement of that goal."},
{id:1570,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a minimum viable product (MVP) and how does it relate to test planning?",options:["A. A product with minimum test coverage","B. A product built by a minimum team size","C. The smallest version of the product that delivers value to users â€” test planning for an MVP focuses on the core features that must work correctly","D. A product released without any testing"],answer:2,explanation:"MVP testing focuses on the core feature set â€” ensuring the essential user journeys work correctly while deferring edge-case testing to later increments."},
{id:1571,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is exploratory testing's role in an Agile test strategy?",options:["A. It complements scripted and automated testing by discovering unexpected defects and testing complex scenarios that are hard to script","B. It replaces all scripted testing","C. It is only used for regression testing","D. It is not part of a formal test strategy"],answer:0,explanation:"Exploratory testing fills the gaps that scripted and automated tests cannot â€” it is a first-class component of a balanced Agile test strategy."},
{id:1572,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team identifies that a new payment gateway integration has never been tested under production-level load. How should this affect test planning?",options:["A. It should be ignored because performance testing is out of scope","B. The integration should be removed from the release","C. Performance and load testing of the integration should be added to the test plan as a high-priority activity","D. The risk should be logged and reviewed next sprint"],answer:2,explanation:"An untested integration under production load is a high product risk â€” performance testing must be explicitly planned before release."},
{id:1573,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team's test environment is shared with another team causing constant conflicts. What type of risk is this?",options:["A. Product risk","B. Business risk","C. Technical debt","D. Project risk â€” environment contention delays testing and threatens the sprint goal"],answer:3,explanation:"Shared environment conflicts are a project risk â€” they block testing progress and introduce delays that threaten sprint delivery."},
{id:1574,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is mob testing and how does it support whole-team quality?",options:["A. Testing done by an angry group of stakeholders","B. The whole team testing together simultaneously â€” sharing knowledge and perspectives to find defects collaboratively","C. A technique where one tester tests while others watch","D. Automated testing run by all team members at once"],answer:1,explanation:"Mob testing brings the whole team together to test collaboratively â€” it builds shared quality understanding and often finds defects that individual testing misses."},
{id:1575,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the spike story and how does it support risk management in iteration planning?",options:["A. A time-boxed research story used to investigate an unknown or risky technical area before committing to implementation","B. A story with very high story points","C. A story that contains only testing tasks","D. A story that is carried over from the previous sprint"],answer:0,explanation:"A spike story reduces risk by investigating unknowns â€” teams use spikes to gain knowledge before committing to implementation of risky stories."},
{id:1576,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"easy",question:"At what stage should risk identification begin in Agile?",options:["A. Only after development is complete","B. At the start of system testing","C. During the sprint retrospective","D. As early as possible â€” during backlog refinement and sprint planning before development starts"],answer:3,explanation:"Early risk identification â€” during refinement and planning â€” is far more cost-effective than discovering risks after they have materialised."},
{id:1577,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is residual risk?",options:["A. The total amount of risk at project start","B. A risk that has already occurred","C. The risk that remains after mitigation actions have been applied","D. A risk that affects only the test environment"],answer:2,explanation:"Residual risk is what remains after mitigation â€” the team and PO must decide if this level of residual risk is acceptable before releasing."},
{id:1578,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What makes Agile test planning lightweight?",options:["A. It has no documentation at all","B. It contains only the information needed to guide the team â€” just enough just in time without unnecessary detail","C. It is written entirely by the tester","D. It is fixed at the start of the project"],answer:1,explanation:"Lightweight test planning provides just enough guidance without excessive documentation â€” it is living and updated regularly."},
{id:1579,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a risk owner in Agile risk management?",options:["A. The team member responsible for monitoring and driving mitigation actions for a specific risk","B. The person who caused the risk","C. The Product Owner who accepts all risks","D. An external risk auditor"],answer:0,explanation:"A risk owner is accountable for ensuring mitigation actions are taken and the risk status is monitored â€” distributing ownership prevents risks from being forgotten."},
{id:1580,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the MAIN purpose of using historical data in test estimation?",options:["A. To prove that the team is improving","B. To assign blame for past estimation errors","C. To use actual past effort as a baseline for forecasting future testing effort more accurately","D. To calculate velocity"],answer:2,explanation:"Historical data grounds estimates in reality â€” using past actuals reduces the reliance on guesswork and improves forecast accuracy."},
{id:1581,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does risk-based testing interact with exploratory testing?",options:["A. They are mutually exclusive approaches","B. Exploratory testing replaces risk assessment","C. Risk-based testing makes exploratory testing unnecessary","D. Risk-based testing identifies the high-risk areas that exploratory testing should then investigate in depth"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk identification feeds exploratory testing â€” knowing which areas are riskiest directs the explorer's focus for maximum defect-finding effectiveness."},
{id:1582,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What responsibility does the Scrum Master have in Agile test planning?",options:["A. Writing test cases","B. Removing impediments that block test planning and ensuring the team has the conditions needed for effective quality activities","C. Approving all test plans","D. Deciding which stories need testing"],answer:1,explanation:"The Scrum Master serves the team by removing obstacles â€” including anything that prevents effective test planning or execution."},
{id:1583,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team always leaves non-functional testing for the last sprint. What is the MOST significant risk?",options:["A. Performance security and usability defects found in the last sprint are very costly to fix and may delay the release","B. Non-functional testing will take too long","C. Non-functional testing is not needed in Agile","D. The Product Owner will accept low performance"],answer:0,explanation:"Late non-functional testing discovers expensive-to-fix issues â€” these concerns should be tested incrementally throughout the release."},
{id:1584,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a feature freeze in release planning?",options:["A. Freezing the product backlog permanently","B. A sprint with no development work","C. A meeting where features are reviewed by stakeholders","D. A point at which no new features are added â€” allowing the team to focus on stabilisation testing and defect fixing before release"],answer:3,explanation:"A feature freeze marks the point where no new features are added â€” this enables the team to focus testing effort on stabilisation and quality assurance."},
{id:1585,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is contract testing and when is it relevant in an Agile test strategy?",options:["A. Testing compliance with legal contracts","B. Verifying that service interfaces between components match the agreed contract â€” especially important in microservices and API-heavy architectures","C. Testing performed by external contracted testers","D. A type of acceptance testing done by the customer"],answer:1,explanation:"Contract testing validates API and service boundaries â€” in microservices architectures it prevents integration failures caused by mismatched interface expectations."},
{id:1586,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is an example of a non-functional product risk?",options:["A. A button not saving user data","B. A form not validating email addresses","C. The application being too slow under peak load to meet the SLA","D. A feature returning incorrect calculation results"],answer:2,explanation:"Non-functional risks relate to quality attributes like performance â€” an application that is too slow under load is a non-functional product risk."},
{id:1587,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is scope creep and why is it a project risk in Agile?",options:["A. Uncontrolled addition of features without adjusting time or capacity â€” it inflates work beyond what the team can test and deliver with quality","B. Adding too many automated tests","C. A tester asking too many questions","D. A sprint that lasts too long"],answer:0,explanation:"Scope creep inflates work beyond the team's capacity â€” testing quality suffers as the team tries to cover more features with the same resources."},
{id:1588,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a risk workshop?",options:["A. A formal audit of the test plan","B. A retrospective focused on quality","C. A facilitated session where the whole team systematically identifies and discusses potential risks to the product or project","D. A training session on risk management tools"],answer:2,explanation:"A risk workshop is a structured collaborative session to surface risks â€” diverse team perspectives catch more risks than any individual can identify alone."},
{id:1589,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is just-enough documentation in Agile test planning?",options:["A. The minimum legal documentation required","B. No documentation at all","C. A full test plan document for every sprint","D. Documentation that provides sufficient guidance without unnecessary detail â€” enough to inform decisions and enable testing"],answer:3,explanation:"Just-enough documentation avoids waste â€” it provides the information needed to test effectively without bureaucratic overhead."},
{id:1590,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does it mean to quantify a risk?",options:["A. Naming the risk","B. Assigning numerical values to the probability and impact to calculate a risk score that can be compared and prioritised","C. Adding the risk to the product backlog","D. Assigning a risk to a team member"],answer:1,explanation:"Quantifying risks assigns numerical probability and impact scores enabling objective prioritisation and comparison of risks."},
{id:1591,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"Why is it important to limit work in progress during iteration planning?",options:["A. To prevent the team from taking on more work than can be completed and tested to a high quality within the sprint","B. To make the sprint board look cleaner","C. To give testers more time to write test plans","D. Because the Scrum Guide requires it"],answer:0,explanation:"Limiting WIP ensures the team commits to a realistic scope â€” avoiding overcommitment that leads to incomplete or poorly tested stories at sprint end."},
{id:1592,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does quality built in mean in Agile?",options:["A. Testing is done by an external QA team","B. All code must pass 100% test coverage","C. A dedicated quality team approves each sprint","D. Quality is considered and activities are designed to prevent defects at every step rather than relying on end-of-sprint testing"],answer:3,explanation:"Built-in quality means every team member and every process contributes to preventing defects rather than finding them after the fact."},
{id:1593,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team identifies that a complex algorithm has never been independently reviewed. What is the BEST mitigation?",options:["A. Add it to the next release backlog","B. Trust the developer who wrote it","C. Schedule a technical code review and add targeted boundary-value and equivalence partitioning tests for the algorithm","D. Only test the algorithm if it fails in production"],answer:2,explanation:"Unreviewed complex algorithms are high risk â€” code review combined with targeted testing applies multiple mitigation layers."},
{id:1594,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a risk-based test prioritisation matrix?",options:["A. A matrix that ranks testers by performance","B. A tool that maps test cases to risk levels so the most important tests are executed first","C. A project timeline showing testing milestones","D. A comparison of test automation tools"],answer:1,explanation:"A risk-based prioritisation matrix ensures high-risk test cases are executed first â€” maximising defect detection within any time constraint."},
{id:1595,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a buffer in test planning and when should it be used?",options:["A. A small reserve of time or effort allocated in the plan to absorb unexpected complexity or defect investigation","B. A tool for storing test results","C. Extra story points added to all estimates","D. A spare tester kept on standby"],answer:0,explanation:"Buffers absorb the inevitable surprises â€” unexpected defects environment issues and estimation errors â€” without blowing the sprint commitment."},
{id:1596,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does acceptance test-driven development support sprint planning?",options:["A. It replaces sprint planning entirely","B. It is only relevant for unit tests","C. Writing acceptance tests before coding starts clarifies requirements and makes testing effort estimable at planning time","D. ATDD reduces the number of stories that can fit in a sprint"],answer:2,explanation:"ATDD produces clear acceptance tests before coding â€” this clarity makes testing effort predictable and estimable during sprint planning."},
{id:1597,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is technical debt and how does it affect release planning?",options:["A. Money owed to external software vendors","B. The cost of the testing infrastructure","C. Story points not completed in previous sprints","D. Shortcuts and deferred quality work that accumulate over time â€” technical debt increases testing effort and risk for future releases"],answer:3,explanation:"Technical debt increases risk and testing effort â€” release planning must account for technical debt remediation to prevent quality degradation over time."},
{id:1598,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has a microservices architecture with 15 services. What testing strategy concern is MOST critical?",options:["A. Writing more unit tests","B. Integration and contract testing between services is critical â€” the interfaces are where failures most commonly occur in this architecture","C. Running more UI tests","D. Increasing story point estimation"],answer:1,explanation:"In microservices architectures service integration points are the highest risk â€” contract and integration testing must be a core strategic concern."},
{id:1599,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"How should accessibility risk be treated in Agile test planning?",options:["A. Accessibility is a non-functional quality attribute â€” it should be included in acceptance criteria and tested incrementally each sprint","B. It should be deferred to a dedicated accessibility sprint at the end","C. Accessibility is only relevant for public sector projects","D. It is the UX designer's responsibility alone"],answer:0,explanation:"Accessibility is a quality attribute like performance â€” testing it incrementally every sprint is far cheaper than a late-stage accessibility retrofit."},
{id:1600,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team uses a third-party testing tool that is no longer being maintained. What is the project risk and what action should be taken?",options:["A. No risk â€” the tool works today","B. Ask the vendor to resume maintenance","C. Ignore the risk until the tool breaks","D. Tool obsolescence is a project risk â€” the team should plan migration to a maintained alternative before the tool causes test failures or security issues"],answer:3,explanation:"Unmaintained tools are a latent project risk â€” security vulnerabilities compatibility breaks and lack of support can cause testing failures at the worst possible time."},
{id:1601,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has separate development and testing silos with no cross-collaboration. What is the MOST harmful consequence for test planning?",options:["A. Testing takes longer","B. Testability problems are discovered late â€” developers code features without considering how they will be tested causing rework","C. The CI pipeline becomes slower","D. The retrospective becomes less useful"],answer:1,explanation:"Siloed teams produce untestable code â€” testability must be considered during development not after it meaning testers must be involved from story creation."},
{id:1602,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team skips risk assessment during iteration planning to save time. Over three sprints production defects double. What is the most likely connection?",options:["A. Production defects are unrelated to iteration planning","B. The testers worked too slowly","C. Without risk assessment high-risk areas receive the same test coverage as low-risk areas â€” high-risk defects escape more easily","D. The Product Owner added too many stories"],answer:2,explanation:"Skipping risk assessment means testing is distributed uniformly rather than focused on highest-risk areas â€” high-risk defects are more likely to escape."},
{id:1603,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a dependency risk and how should it be managed in Agile?",options:["A. A risk arising from reliance on external teams systems or components â€” managed by identifying dependencies early and planning integration testing","B. The risk that a team member depends too much on one tool","C. A risk that a story depends on another story in the backlog","D. Only relevant in traditional waterfall projects"],answer:0,explanation:"Dependency risks arise from external reliance â€” identifying them early and planning explicit integration testing prevents late-sprint surprises."},
{id:1604,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has identified 50 risks but rates them all as high to ensure they all get attention. What is wrong with this approach?",options:["A. Nothing â€” more attention on all risks is always better","B. It creates too much work for the Scrum Master","C. If everything is high priority nothing is â€” true risk assessment discriminates so resources go to the genuinely highest risks","D. The Product Owner should assign risk levels not the team"],answer:2,explanation:"Risk inflation defeats the purpose of risk management â€” if all risks are high the team cannot prioritise and critical risks receive no more attention than trivial ones."},
{id:1605,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team finds a high-risk defect in a feature that has already been reviewed and approved by the PO. What is the BEST course of action?",options:["A. Release the feature anyway because the PO approved it","B. Fix the defect without informing anyone","C. Log it and address it in the next sprint without escalation","D. Immediately communicate the risk to the PO with evidence â€” the PO must make an informed decision on deferral fixing or accepting the risk"],answer:3,explanation:"Transparent communication of a high-risk finding to the PO is mandatory â€” the PO must knowingly choose between fix defer or accept with full awareness of the impact."},
{id:1606,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team applies risk-based testing and releases with no critical defects but many minor usability issues. What conclusion is MOST appropriate?",options:["A. Risk-based testing failed","B. Risk-based testing correctly prioritised functional correctness â€” usability risks were rated lower and received less coverage which should be reassessed for next release","C. The team should add more testers","D. Usability testing is not part of Agile testing"],answer:1,explanation:"The outcome shows that usability risks were under-weighted in the risk assessment â€” this is useful feedback for improving the risk model next release."},
{id:1607,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"hard",question:"Why is it important to re-estimate testing effort when a story's scope changes mid-sprint?",options:["A. Because the original estimate no longer reflects reality â€” unchanged estimates create false confidence and increase the risk of untested scope","B. To track changes for billing purposes","C. The Scrum Master requires it","D. It is not necessary â€” the original estimate is sufficient"],answer:0,explanation:"A scope change invalidates the original estimate â€” proceeding with an outdated estimate means the team may not have planned enough testing capacity."},
{id:1608,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester identifies that a critical story depends on a third-party API that has not yet been integrated. The sprint starts in two days. What should happen?",options:["A. Accept the story and test it once the API is available during the sprint","B. Accept the story and skip testing the API integration","C. Ask the tester to mock the API themselves","D. Flag the dependency as a blocker â€” if it cannot be resolved before the sprint starts the story should not enter the sprint"],answer:3,explanation:"Unresolved external dependencies are a testability risk â€” a story dependent on an unavailable component cannot be reliably completed or tested within the sprint."},
{id:1609,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"hard",question:"A company wants to release monthly but their regression suite takes 3 days to run manually. What should the release plan address?",options:["A. Reduce the regression suite to fit within one day","B. Release fortnightly instead","C. Automate the regression suite â€” manual regression at that scale is incompatible with monthly release cadence","D. Remove non-critical regression tests permanently"],answer:2,explanation:"A 3-day manual regression cycle is incompatible with monthly releases â€” automation is the necessary investment to sustain the release cadence."},
{id:1610,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the role of non-regression testing in an Agile test strategy?",options:["A. Non-regression testing is only done once per release","B. Non-regression testing verifies old features are not broken by new changes â€” it is essential in Agile where frequent changes could break existing functionality","C. Non-regression testing is replaced by exploratory testing in Agile","D. Non-regression testing is only relevant in waterfall projects"],answer:1,explanation:"Regression testing is foundational in Agile â€” every sprint's changes risk breaking previously working functionality so regression coverage is critical."},
{id:1611,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team is building an autonomous vehicle control module. How should product risk identification differ from a typical business application?",options:["A. Safety-critical systems require structured hazard analysis regulatory compliance review and independent verification â€” risk identification must be far more rigorous and formal","B. No difference â€” the same lightweight Agile approach applies","C. Risk identification is the same but testing takes longer","D. Only the Product Owner needs to identify risks"],answer:0,explanation:"Safety-critical systems have life-and-safety stakes â€” standard Agile lightweight risk approaches are insufficient and formal hazard analysis methods are required."},
{id:1612,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team has been asked to deliver a product with no test environment â€” they must test directly in production. What is the PRIMARY risk and recommended response?",options:["A. The team should agree and test in production","B. Refuse to test until a proper environment is provided","C. Testing in production is a severe project risk â€” advocate for a staging environment and use feature flags canary releases and automated rollback to minimise production risk if staging cannot be provided","D. Ask the Scrum Master to resolve it"],answer:2,explanation:"Production testing without a staging environment is extremely high risk â€” modern progressive delivery techniques can partially mitigate it but a staging environment is strongly preferable."},
{id:1613,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team uses only retrospective feedback to identify risks. What is the MOST critical weakness?",options:["A. Retrospectives are too infrequent","B. Retrospectives focus too much on positive feedback","C. Only the Scrum Master facilitates retrospectives","D. Retrospectives are backward-looking â€” by the time a risk is discussed in a retrospective it has already materialised and caused harm"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk management must be proactive and forward-looking â€” retrospective-only risk identification is reactive and misses risks before they cause damage."},
{id:1614,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A risk has been rated as low for five consecutive sprints. A team member argues it can be removed from the risk register. What is the BEST counter-argument?",options:["A. All risks must stay on the register forever","B. Low-rated risks should be retained and periodically reviewed â€” circumstances change and a risk that is low today may become high as the product evolves","C. Remove it to simplify the register","D. Ask the Product Owner to decide"],answer:1,explanation:"Risk registers should be living documents â€” risks should be retained and periodically reassessed rather than removed just because they are currently low."},
{id:1615,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team has mitigated all identified risks but a production incident still occurs from an unidentified risk. What does this indicate?",options:["A. Risk identification was incomplete â€” unknown unknowns exist and the team should use techniques like chaos engineering and exploratory testing to surface them proactively","B. The mitigation was ineffective","C. Risk management is not useful in Agile","D. The team should stop risk management activities"],answer:0,explanation:"Unknown risks (unknown unknowns) cannot be mitigated if never identified â€” techniques like chaos engineering and broad exploratory testing help surface them before they cause harm."},
{id:1616,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Estimation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team is asked to provide a fixed-price test effort estimate for a year-long Agile project at the outset. What is the BEST response?",options:["A. Provide a precise estimate based on the backlog","B. Refuse to estimate until the project is complete","C. Provide the estimate and add a 100% contingency","D. Explain that Agile's evolving scope makes precise long-range estimates unreliable â€” provide a rough order-of-magnitude range and commit to re-estimating at each release planning milestone"],answer:3,explanation:"Long-range estimates in Agile are inherently uncertain â€” cone of uncertainty principles mean rough ranges at release boundaries are more honest and useful than false-precision single-point estimates."},
{id:1617,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's sprint planning consistently takes 4 hours but produces unclear testing tasks. What is the ROOT problem to address?",options:["A. Sprint planning is too short","B. Stories are entering planning without sufficient acceptance criteria â€” backlog refinement is inadequate meaning planning time is spent clarifying rather than planning","C. The tester talks too much in planning","D. The Scrum Master is not facilitating effectively"],answer:1,explanation:"Poor sprint planning quality usually traces back to poor backlog refinement â€” stories that arrive at planning half-baked force clarification discussions that should have happened earlier."},
{id:1618,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"Midway through a release a competitor launches a similar product forcing a 6-week release date acceleration. What must the test plan address?",options:["A. Cut all testing to hit the date","B. Refuse to accelerate","C. Immediately reassess risks re-prioritise testing to critical user journeys apply risk-based test selection and explicitly accept residual risk â€” communicate tradeoffs to stakeholders","D. Add more testers and keep the original plan"],answer:2,explanation:"Accelerated release requires explicit risk-based triage â€” the team must identify what testing is non-negotiable protect it and make conscious informed decisions about what is deferred."},
{id:1619,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's test strategy has never been revised in 18 months despite major architectural changes. What is the MOST likely consequence?",options:["A. The strategy no longer reflects the actual system â€” testing may be misaligned with current risks and architecture leaving real gaps uncovered","B. The strategy becomes more accurate over time","C. An outdated strategy still provides useful guidance","D. Only the test manager needs to update it"],answer:0,explanation:"An outdated test strategy creates false confidence â€” it may direct testing effort at obsolete risks while missing new risks introduced by architectural evolution."},
{id:1620,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"In a team where quality has deteriorated despite all members attending quality meetings what is the MOST likely root cause?",options:["A. The meetings are too long","B. The tester is not skilled enough","C. Quality activities are discussed but not actioned â€” whole-team quality requires behavioural change not just meeting attendance","D. The Scrum Master is not doing their job"],answer:2,explanation:"Attending quality meetings without changing behaviour achieves nothing â€” whole-team quality requires everyone to actively apply quality practices in their daily work."},
{id:1621,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team applies risk-based testing rigorously but the Product Owner consistently overrides risk priorities based on personal preference. What is the PRIMARY consequence?",options:["A. The team delivers faster","B. The PO improves test quality","C. Risk-based testing becomes unnecessary","D. Risk-based prioritisation is undermined â€” high-risk areas may receive insufficient coverage while low-risk PO-favoured areas are over-tested"],answer:3,explanation:"Effective risk-based testing requires that risk ratings drive prioritisation â€” overriding them with preferences breaks the model and creates coverage gaps where it matters most."},
{id:1622,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Iteration Planning",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team skips refinement and goes directly to sprint planning for every story. Over time what is the MOST significant impact on test planning?",options:["A. Sprint planning becomes faster","B. Stories arrive at sprint planning too vague for testing to be planned â€” acceptance criteria are unclear testability is unassessed and estimates are unreliable","C. The team delivers more features","D. Testing improves because the team has more autonomy"],answer:1,explanation:"Without refinement stories arrive at planning half-baked â€” testers cannot plan testing for stories they do not understand and estimation becomes guesswork."},
{id:1623,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team builds a healthcare data application. Which of the following is the HIGHEST product risk?",options:["A. Patient data being accessible to unauthorised users due to inadequate access controls","B. The UI colour scheme is not preferred by all users","C. Reports loading 2 seconds slower than the target SLA","D. A minor spelling error in a non-critical help page"],answer:0,explanation:"Unauthorised access to patient data is a catastrophic risk â€” regulatory legal and safety consequences make this the highest priority risk to mitigate."},
{id:1624,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has no documented test environment setup procedure. A new tester joins. What project risk does this create?",options:["A. No risk â€” the new tester will figure it out","B. The environment will break","C. The Product Owner will be unhappy","D. Onboarding the new tester is slow and error-prone â€” undocumented procedures create a knowledge bottleneck and project risk"],answer:3,explanation:"Undocumented critical procedures are a project risk â€” knowledge locked in individuals' heads creates bottlenecks and onboarding delays."},
{id:1625,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team is integrating with a legacy system for the first time. What is the FIRST risk identification step?",options:["A. Start testing immediately","B. Write acceptance criteria","C. Arrange a technical deep-dive with the legacy system owner to understand its behaviour failure modes and integration constraints","D. Add integration tests to the regression suite"],answer:2,explanation:"Understanding an unknown system requires knowledge gathering first â€” engaging its owners surfaces hidden risks that would otherwise only be discovered through painful trial and error."},
{id:1626,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a risk threshold in Agile testing?",options:["A. The maximum number of test cases allowed","B. The agreed level of risk exposure above which active mitigation is required","C. The minimum story points for a sprint","D. The maximum number of defects allowed in a release"],answer:1,explanation:"A risk threshold defines the line above which a risk must be actively mitigated rather than accepted â€” it provides a consistent criterion for risk response decisions."},
{id:1627,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is test-driven risk mitigation?",options:["A. Writing tests specifically targeting identified risk areas to either confirm the risk is realised or provide evidence it is mitigated","B. Using TDD to write unit tests","C. A risk management tool for testers","D. Running all tests before identifying any risks"],answer:0,explanation:"Writing targeted tests for known risk areas is a direct mitigation â€” if the tests pass the risk is addressed if they fail the risk is confirmed and can be fixed."},
{id:1628,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a test approach document in Agile and what should it contain?",options:["A. A 50-page formal plan for the entire project","B. A list of all test cases to be executed","C. A brief living document describing testing scope techniques tools levels and entry and exit criteria â€” updated each sprint","D. A record of defects found in previous sprints"],answer:2,explanation:"An Agile test approach document is brief and living â€” it aligns the team on how testing will be done without drowning in documentation overhead."},
{id:1629,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does continuous integration support the whole-team approach to test planning?",options:["A. CI replaces manual test planning","B. CI only runs the tester's tests","C. CI is unrelated to test planning","D. CI makes automated test results visible to the whole team immediately â€” quality information is shared without waiting for a tester to report"],answer:3,explanation:"CI democratises quality information â€” every team member can see test results in real time making quality a whole-team visible concern not a tester's private report."},
{id:1630,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk-Based Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team decides to skip edge-case testing on a low-risk feature to save time. This is an example of:",options:["A. Poor testing practice","B. Risk-based test prioritisation â€” consciously allocating less coverage to lower-risk areas to free capacity for higher-risk ones","C. Test avoidance","D. A Definition of Done violation"],answer:1,explanation:"Consciously reducing coverage on low-risk features to focus effort on high-risk ones is exactly what risk-based testing prescribes â€” not poor practice."},
{id:1631,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Sprint Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the minimum input a tester needs to plan testing for a story in sprint planning?",options:["A. Clear acceptance criteria describing the expected behaviour","B. A complete test plan","C. The source code","D. A list of all previous defects"],answer:0,explanation:"Clear acceptance criteria are the minimum needed for a tester to understand what must be verified â€” without them meaningful test planning is impossible."},
{id:1632,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Release Planning",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the purpose of a go/no-go decision in release planning?",options:["A. To decide whether to start the project","B. To assign responsibilities for the sprint","C. To approve the product backlog","D. To evaluate whether the product meets quality and risk thresholds sufficient to release to users"],answer:3,explanation:"A go/no-go decision gate evaluates whether quality metrics risk levels and exit criteria are met before authorising the release to production."},
{id:1633,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Strategy in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the testing quadrant model and what is its purpose?",options:["A. A model for organising the product backlog","B. A framework that categorises testing activities across two dimensions â€” business-facing vs technology-facing and supporting the team vs critiquing the product","C. A risk assessment matrix","D. A model for measuring sprint velocity"],answer:1,explanation:"The testing quadrants help teams plan a balanced test strategy ensuring business-facing functional tests technical tests exploratory tests and non-functional tests are all considered."},
{id:1634,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Product Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team is about to release a feature that has had 3 critical defects fixed in the past week. How should this affect test planning?",options:["A. No change â€” the defects have been fixed","B. The feature should be removed from the release","C. The feature should be treated as high risk â€” areas with a recent high defect density warrant additional focused regression testing","D. Testing should be reduced because the team has already spent time on it"],answer:2,explanation:"Recent defect density is a strong indicator of risk â€” defect clustering in one area suggests underlying issues making thorough regression critical before release."},
{id:1635,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Project Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team discovers that their automated test suite is not being maintained and is producing false positives. What project risk does this create?",options:["A. The CI pipeline loses credibility â€” developers start ignoring failing tests and real defects can be masked by noise","B. Tests run too slowly","C. The tester will have less work","D. Story points will be affected"],answer:0,explanation:"An unreliable test suite erodes trust â€” once developers start ignoring failures the entire quality safety net is compromised and defects can ship undetected."},
{id:1636,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Identification",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does a tester add value during backlog refinement from a risk perspective?",options:["A. By approving all stories","B. By writing all acceptance criteria","C. By identifying testability issues ambiguous acceptance criteria and hidden risks before stories are committed to a sprint","D. By assigning story point estimates"],answer:2,explanation:"Testers in refinement are risk detectors â€” they spot ambiguities and testability problems that would otherwise only surface as defects during or after the sprint."},
{id:1637,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Assessment",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team uses a 1-5 scale for both likelihood and impact and multiplies the scores. A risk scored 4Ã—4=16 and another 5Ã—2=10. Which should be prioritised?",options:["A. The 5Ã—2 risk because the probability is higher","B. Both equally because they are close in score","C. Neither â€” both scores are too low to act on","D. The 4Ã—4 risk because the combined risk exposure score is higher"],answer:3,explanation:"Risk prioritisation is based on the combined exposure score â€” a 16 outranks a 10 regardless of which individual dimension is higher."},
{id:1638,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Risk Mitigation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is regression testing's role in ongoing risk mitigation in Agile?",options:["A. Regression testing only mitigates risks from new features","B. Regression testing continuously verifies that changes have not introduced new risks into previously working functionality","C. Regression testing replaces risk assessment","D. Regression testing is a one-time activity"],answer:1,explanation:"Regression testing is a continuous mitigation activity â€” every sprint's changes risk destabilising existing functionality and regression tests catch this."},
{id:1639,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Whole-Team Test Planning",difficulty:"medium",question:"A developer refuses to write unit tests claiming that is the tester's job. How does this conflict with Agile quality principles?",options:["A. Whole-team quality means everyone contributes to quality â€” developers are responsible for unit tests as part of their coding practice","B. The developer is correct â€” testers own all test types","C. The Scrum Master should decide who writes unit tests","D. Unit tests are optional in Agile"],answer:0,explanation:"Whole-team quality means developers own unit testing â€” quality is not delegated to testers but shared across all roles."},
{id:1640,chapter:"Agile Test Planning and Risk Management",topic:"Test Planning in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team is transitioning from traditional waterfall testing to Agile. What is the MOST important mindset shift for the tester?",options:["A. From manual testing to fully automated testing overnight","B. From working with developers to working alone","C. From testing at the end to testing only at the start","D. From writing comprehensive test plans upfront to planning incrementally and collaborating continuously throughout development"],answer:3,explanation:"The fundamental shift is from sequential phase-based planning to continuous collaborative incremental planning â€” testers become partners in quality from day one not inspectors at the end."}
